%N A279281 Expansion of Product_{k>=1} (1 + x^(k*(3*k-2))).
%C A279281 Number of partitions of n into distinct octagonal numbers (A000567).
%H A279281 Vaclav Kotesovec, <a href="/A279281/b279281.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a> (terms 0..1000 from G. C. Greubel)
%H A279281 Vaclav Kotesovec, <a href="/A279281/a279281.jpg">Graph - the asymptotic ratio (200000 terms)</a>
%H A279281 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/OctagonalNumber.html">Octagonal Number</a>
%H A279281 <a href="/index/Pol#polygonal_numbers">Index to sequences related to polygonal numbers</a>
%H A279281 <a href="/index/Par#partN">Index entries for related partition-counting sequences</a>
%F A279281 G.f.: Product_{k>=1} (1 + x^(k*(3*k-2))).
%F A279281 a(n) ~ zeta(3/2)^(1/3) * (sqrt(2) - 1)^(1/3) * exp(3*Pi^(1/3) * zeta(3/2)^(2/3) * (sqrt(2) - 1)^(2/3) * n^(1/3) / (2^(5/3)*d^(1/3))) / (2^(4/3 + b/(2*d)) * sqrt(3) * d^(1/6) * Pi^(1/3) * n^(5/6)) * (1 - ((sqrt(2) - 1)^(4/3) * b^2 * Pi^(2/3) * zeta(1/2) * zeta(3/2)^(1/3) / (2^(23/6) * d^(5/3)) + 5*d^(1/3) / (9 * (2*Pi)^(1/3) * (sqrt(2) - 1)^(2/3) * zeta(3/2)^(2/3))) / n^(1/3)), where d = 3, b = -2. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 11 2026
%e A279281 a(105) = 2 because we have [96, 8, 1] and [65, 40].
%t A279281 nmax = 120; CoefficientList[Series[Product[1 + x^(k*(3*k-2)), {k, 1, Sqrt[1 + 3*nmax]/3 + 1}], {x, 0, nmax}], x] (* tuned for efficiency by _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 10 2026 *)
